etymologies: late 16th century; earliest use found in Abraham Fraunce (?1559–?1593), poet and lawyer. From post-classical Latin enthymematicus enthymematic + -al

definitions: Of an argument, sentence, etc.: that takes the form of an enthymeme, especially in leaving one or more premises unstated; (also) of the nature of an enthymeme; consisting of or employing enthymemes.
